  <h2>Where We Stand</h2>
  <p>
    Three months out. The 2026 Newport Bermuda Race is in June, and the campaign is on track. Not without problems — there are always problems — but on track. Here's the honest update.
  </p>

  <h2>Printer Integration</h2>
  <p>
    The Prusa CORE One L is arriving. That's confirmed. The integration plan for the boat has been through three revisions because the first two didn't properly account for the angle of heel under sail. A printer that works perfectly on a level bench doesn't work the same way when the boat is heeled 20 degrees in a seaway.
  </p>
  <p>
    We're building a gimbal-style mounting platform. Not motorized — mechanical. Spring-loaded compensation with a locking mechanism for heavy weather when printing stops anyway. The filament path is being routed through a sealed dry box because humidity at sea is a print killer.
  </p>

  <h2>Boat Prep</h2>
  <p>
    CSM's boat is going through its pre-race service. Bottom paint, rigging inspection, electronics check. The usual pre-season work plus the unusual: routing power for the printer, reinforcing the mounting area, and making sure nothing I'm adding compromises the boat's racing trim.
  </p>
  <p>
    The electrical system was a conversation. A CORE One L draws real power. We're running dedicated circuits with a marine-grade inverter that can handle the print head heater and bed heater simultaneously without brownouts. Solar supplementation is being discussed but probably won't happen for this race — the timeline is too tight for a proper installation.
  </p>

  <h2>Materials for the Crossing</h2>
  <p>
    I'm packing three materials for the race: PETG (general purpose, good moisture resistance), ASA (for anything exposed to sun and salt), and TPU (for gaskets, bumpers, vibration dampeners). No PLA — too moisture-sensitive for sustained marine conditions. Each material in sealed vacuum bags with desiccant packs.
  </p>

  <h2>What's Next</h2>
  <p>
    April is shakedown sails. We'll have the printer installed and running test prints while underway in coastal waters. That's where we find out what we missed. May is final prep and qualification. June is the race.
  </p>
  <p>
